originalText.text: I live in East Harlem but this Trader Joe's, some 100 blocks south of me is my local supermarket. I have a few theories about the practices of this magnificent shopping emporium. They do a great job hiding the unhealthy food and will only hire you if you treat every customer discreetly like royalty. Not happy with a prior purchase? Your attending clerk will ring a large, brass, wall-mounted ship's bell and your purchase will be credited by a roving supervisor, no questions asked. You will be asked whether you had found everything you were looking for "today?" Well, truthfully, not always, but why dampen the enthusiasm?  If you crave fresh fruits and vegetables and healthy salads and sandwiches, this is the place for you. I always compliment the clerk standing on the platform directing the stream of single file customers to numbered cashiers. "Nothing ever happens around here without you!"  They smile knowingly.  Marvelous!

originalText.text: I was racially discriminated at this location on Thursday February 8th 2024, at approximately 4:30 pm - 4:45pm. The moment I stepped into the store, the security guard was following me the entire time. I was at the store for approximately 30-45 minutes and this man kept following me and making me uncomfortable. I noticed immediately that he was following and called him out and asked him why was he following me. He lied in my face and said that he wasn‚Äôt. Afterwards he kept on following me everywhere I went and kept staring at me the entire time. At one point he lost sight of me and when he found me, he ran towards me again. When I went to check out I told Shaun who is one of the managers of what occurred and they made excuses for his behavior and said that they have no control on what they do because they are a third party. When I purchased my items the security guard went back to his post in front of the store and I confronted him again because he made my shopping experience horrendous and unbearable. That‚Äôs when another manager named Nick intervened and asked what happened. I explained to him what occurred and he made excuses and said that‚Äôs normal for security to follow people in the store. I have been shopping at Trader Joe's for over 12 years now and I have never experienced something like this before, the lack of empathy from management really rubbed me the wrong way. We're in 2024 and people still want to follow Black people in the store without no reason whatsoever other than being Black.
